UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2104
1 each week in which he or she claims eligibility. At least three (3) of these
2 activities each week shall consist of formally submitting an application for
3 employment or interviewing for employment. "Work search activities"
4 includes any of the following:
5 1. Formally submitting an application for employment, either in person or
6 online;
7 2. Interviewing for employment virtually, in person, or online;
8 3. Job shadowing;
9 4. Attending a job fair or networking event hosted by state or local
10 government or a business organization;
11 5. Participating in a job search skills workshop or seminar; and
12 6. Participating in official Kentucky Career Center or partner programs
13 related to employment or the search for employment;
14 (4) He or she is physically and mentally able to work;
15 (5) He or she is available for suitable work, and making such reasonable effort to
16 obtain work as might be expected of a prudent person under like circumstances;
17 (6) His or her base-period wages in that calendar quarter of his or her base period in
18 which such wages were highest are equal to at least one thousand five hundred
19 dollars ($1,500), and his or her total base-period wages are not less than one and
20 one-half (1-1/2) times the base-period wages paid to him or her in such quarter and
21 he or she was paid base-period wages in the last six (6) months of his or her base
22 period equal to at least eight (8) times his or her weekly benefit rate with a
23 minimum of one thousand five hundred dollars ($1,500) earned outside the high
24 quarter. Beginning on January 1, 2020, and continuing on January 1 in even-
25 numbered years thereafter, the secretary shall adjust the minimum base-period
26 wages at a rate that is directly proportional to the average percentage change in the
27 Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers (CPI-U) for the two (2) previous
Page 2 of 4
XXXX 2/20/2026 7:56 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2104
1 calendar years;
2 (7) An otherwise eligible worker shall not be denied benefits under subsection (5) of
3 this section or because of his or her failure to actively seek work under subsection
4 (3) of this section, nor disqualified under paragraph (a) of subsection (1) of KRS
5 341.370:
6 (a) With respect to any week he or she is certified as being enrolled and making
7 satisfactory progress in an approved job training or certification program;[ or]
8 (b) If he or she has verified definite return-to-work or recall-to-work prospects
9 within a period of twelve (12) months[sixteen (16) weeks] from the date of
10 filing of the initial or reopened claim; or
11 (c) If his or her place of employment becomes nonoperational due to a natural
12 disaster and can reasonably be expected to resume operations within twelve
13 (12) months from the date of the natural disaster.
14 (8) Notwithstanding any other provisions of this chapter, no otherwise eligible worker
15 shall be denied benefits for any week because he or she is in training approved
16 under 19 U.S.C. sec. 2296 (Section 236(a)(1) of the Trade Act of 1974), nor shall
17 such worker be denied benefits by reason of leaving work to enter such training
18 provided such work is not suitable employment, or because of the application to any
19 such week in training of provisions in this law (or any applicable federal
20 unemployment compensation law) relating to availability for work, active search
21 for work, or refusal to accept work. For purpose of this subsection, the term
22 "suitable employment" shall mean employment of a substantially equal or higher
23 skill level than the worker's past adversely affected employment as defined in 19
24 U.S.C. sec. 2319 (Trade Act of 1974), and wages for such work are not less than
25 eighty percent (80%) of the workers' average weekly wage as determined for
26 purposes of the Trade Act of 1974.
27 (9) The foregoing eligibility requirements and the conditions of benefit
Page 3 of 4
XXXX 2/20/2026 7:56 AM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2104
1 disqualifications imposed by KRS 341.370 shall be strictly construed. Nothing in
2 this section, excepting subsection (6) of this section, nor in KRS 341.360 or
3 341.370 shall affect the establishment of a "benefit year."
4 (10) The cabinet shall conduct randomized weekly audits of a number determined by the
5 secretary as sufficient to evaluate compliance with the work search activity
6 requirements of this section, and shall submit an annual report to the Governor and
7 the Interim Joint Committee on Economic Development and Workforce Investment
8 detailing:
9 (a) The percentage of audited claimants that failed to comply with the work
10 search activity requirement outlined in this section;
11 (b) The work search activities that were most commonly engaged in by audited
12 claimants;
13 (c) Recommendations to make the work search activity requirement more
14 effective in assisting claimants in finding employment;
15 (d) The number of claims audited each week and the total number of claims
16 audited during the reporting period;
17 (e) The percentage of total claims audited each week and percentage of total
18 claims audited during the reporting period; and
19 (f) A summary of the methodology used to conduct randomized auditing.
20 (11) The secretary shall promulgate regulations and standards for the verification of
21 claimants' work search activities and the methods by which claimants shall submit
22 work search activities and any associated documentation required by the secretary
23 for verification.
